Have you ever thought? Why is the blackhole of the movie Interstellar, named Gargantua, different from the actual blackhole image released by NASA? Well, there is an explanation for this by the movie physicist, Kip Throne. Professor Kip Thorne is a famous theoretical physicist. He was a great friend of Stephen Hawking and Carl Sagan and was also Richard Feynman's professor of theoretical physics . He shared a Nobel Prize in Physics in 2017 together with Weiss and Barish. He is a world-leading expert on the implications of Einstein's theory of general relativity, from time travels to wormholes and from black holes to gravitational waves. He was executive producer and scientific adviser for the Movie Interstellar, the 2014 blockbuster film. One of Kip's key contributions was the visualisation of black holes and their surroundings, which contributed to the film winning an Oscar for "Best Visual Effects." Kip explained the science in the film in his 2014 book The Science of Interstellar. ☆▪︎☆▪︎☆ Video credit and repost by my friend @modernsciencex ☆▪︎☆▪︎☆ IF YOU APPRECIATE OUR PAGES 🌐FOLLOW @glamour_physics @modernsciencex ☆▪︎☆▪︎☆ For more content EDUCATIONAL PURPOSES ONLY 🌐FOLLOW @glamour_physics ☆▪︎☆▪︎☆ For the pics used in this uploaded editing: All Rights And Credits Reserved To Respected Owner (s) Content Is Used For Educational Purposes Only No copyright infringement intended .
